00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:53.300
Lifestyle influences our neurophysiology,

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:55.680
so lonely people perceive the world very differently.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:57.490
For instance, people suffering from loneliness

00:01:57.490 --> 00:02:01.480
tend to see benign events as more threatening,
living in self-defense mode…

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:06.039
even in their sleep. Some research suggests that lonelier
people have more restless sleep patterns,

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:08.140
which could impact cognitive development.

00:02:08.140 --> 00:02:10.780
Research suggests that there are 
neural correlates for loneliness.

00:02:10.780 --> 00:02:14.740
A 2009 study revealed that lonelier people
 showed less activation in brain centers

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:18.500
associated with reward when viewing pictures of people in pleasant situations,

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:20.360
and less activation in parts of the brain linked to empathy

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.180
when viewing images of people
in unpleasant situations.

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:29.060
Other researchers also discovered that neurons in the dorsal raphe nuclei are sensitive to social isolation.

00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:33.100
Those neurons in question, taken together
with the ones from the ventral striatum,

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:35.440
deal with the reward neurotransmitter dopamine.

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:37.819
So, it’s possible that low social interactions

00:02:37.820 --> 00:02:43.080
= less dopamine = less feeling good. Of course,
the latter study was run with mice,

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:44.480
so more research is always needed.

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:47.980
On top of that, a meta-analysis from 1980 to 2015 
found that

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:53.120
loneliness and its accompanying
depression was as bad as smoking 15 cigarettes a day,

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:57.500
and is a risk factor for mortality.
